 Bellingen runner: Gumbaynggirr man Dylan Kelly with netballer Liz Ellis as the baton passed through the main street of Bellingen this afternoon.It's about sharing the dream: the Gold Coast 2018 Commonwealth Games just got that little bit more real with the baton relay heading our way. From April 4 to 15, history will be made on the Gold Coast with the 2018 Commonwealth Games to get underway.Part of sharing the dream is the Queen’s Baton relay, which is heading our way on February 2.There are several local participants in the relay.There are also some significant road closures necessary to ensure the relay goes ahead smoothly. While the Port Macquarie-Hastings is not directly part of the relay, a number of our residents will be participating.Following the Kempsey leg, the baton relay will then move to Forster-Tuncurry.The Gold Coast will welcome more than 6600 athletes and team officials from 70 Commonwealth nations and territories to the Gold Coast and event cities Brisbane, Cairns and Townsville, to share in the celebration of sport, entertainment and culture.The largest sporting event to be staged in Australia this decade, GC2018 will feature the largest integrated sports program in Commonwealth Games history, comprising 18 sports and seven para-sports.Beach Volleyball, Para Triathlon and Women’s Rugby Sevens will make their Commonwealth Games debuts and for the first time at a Commonwealth Games, an equal number of men’s and women’s medal events will be contested.The Gold Coast 2018 Commonwealth Games Corporation (GOLDOC) was established in January 2012. Working with Government and our Games Delivery Partners, GOLDOC’s role is to plan, organise and deliver a great Games in 2018.facebookSHAREtwitterTWEETemailwhatsappcommentComments